# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: count-min-sketch
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] In computing, the **count–min sketch** (**CM sketch**) is a probabilistic data structure that serves as a frequency table of events in a stream of data.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] It uses hash functions to map events to frequencies, but unlike a hash table uses only sub-linear space, at the expense of overcounting some events due to collisions.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] The count–min sketch was invented in 2003 by Graham Cormode and S.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] Muthu Muthukrishnan and described by them in a 2005 paper.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] Count–min sketch is an alternative to count sketch and AMS sketch and can be considered an implementation of a counting Bloom filter (Fan et al., 1998) or multistage-filter.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] However, they are used differently and therefore sized differently: a count–min sketch typically has a sublinear number of cells, related to the desired approximation quality of the sketch, while a counting Bloom filter is more typically sized to match the number of elements in the set.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] The goal of the basic version of the count–min sketch is to consume a stream of events, one at a time, and count the frequency of the different types of events in the stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] At any time, the sketch can be queried for the frequency of a particular event type i from a universe of event types ${\mathcal {U}}$ , and will return an estimate of this frequency that is within a certain distance of the true frequency, with a certain probability.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] The actual sketch data structure is a two-dimensional array of w columns and d rows.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] The parameters w and d are fixed when the sketch is created, and determine the time and space needs and the probability of error when the sketch is queried for a frequency or inner product.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] Associated with each of the d rows is a separate hash function; the hash functions must be pairwise independent.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] The parameters w and d can be chosen by setting *w* = ⌈*e*/*ε*⌉ and *d* = ⌈ln 1/*δ*⌉, where the error in answering a query is within an additive factor of ε with probability 1 − *δ* (see below), and *e* is Euler's number.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] When a new event of type i arrives we update as follows: for each row j of the table, apply the corresponding hash function to obtain a column index *k* = *h**j*(*i*).
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] Then increment the value in row j, column k by one.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] The *point query* asks for the count of an event type i.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] The estimated count is given by the least value in the table for i, namely ${\hat {a}}_{i}=\min _{j}\mathrm {count} [j,h_{j}(i)]$ , where $\mathrm {count}$ is the table.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] Obviously, for each i, one has $a_{i}\leq {\hat {a}}_{i}$ , where $a_{i}$ is the true frequency with which i occurred in the stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] Additionally, this estimate has the guarantee that ${\hat {a}}_{i}\leq a_{i}+\varepsilon N$ with probability $1-\delta$ , where $N=\sum _{i\in {\mathcal {U}}}a_{i}$ is the stream size, i.e. the total number of items seen by the sketch.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] An *inner product query* asks for the inner product between the histograms represented by two count–min sketches, $\mathrm {count} _{a}$ and $\mathrm {count} _{b}$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] The inner product can then be estimated as ${\widehat {a\cdot b}}=\min _{j}{\widehat {a\cdot b}}_{j}$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] Like the count sketch, the Count–min sketch is a linear sketch.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] That is, given two streams, constructing a sketch on each stream and summing the sketches yields the same result as concatenating the streams and constructing a sketch on the concatenated streams.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] This makes the sketch mergeable and appropriate for use in distributed settings in addition to streaming ones.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] One potential problem with the usual min estimator for count–min sketches is that they are biased estimators of the true frequency of events: they may overestimate, but never underestimate the true count in a point query.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] Furthermore, while the min estimator works well when the distribution is highly skewed, other sketches such as the Count sketch based on means are more accurate when the distribution is not sufficiently skewed.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] Several variations on the sketch have been proposed to reduce error and reduce or eliminate bias.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] To remove bias, the `hCount*` estimator repeatedly randomly selects d random entries in the sketch and takes the minimum to obtain an unbiased estimate of the bias and subtracts it off.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] A maximum likelihood estimator (MLE) was derived in Ting.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] By using the MLE, the estimator is always able to match or better the min estimator and works well even if the distribution is not skewed.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] This paper also showed the hCount* debiasing operation is a bootstrapping procedure that can be efficiently computed without random sampling and can be generalized to any estimator.
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] Since errors arise from hash collisions with unknown items from the universe, several approaches correct for the collisions when multiple elements of the universe are known or queried for simultaneously .
[src:count-min-sketch/count-min-sketch] For each of these, a large proportion of the universe must be known to observe a significant benefit.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] A **data stream management system** (DSMS) is a computer software system to manage continuous data streams.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] It is similar to a database management system (DBMS), which is, however, designed for static data in conventional databases.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] A DBMS also offers a flexible query processing so that the information needed can be expressed using queries.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] However, in contrast to a DBMS, a DSMS executes a *continuous query* that is not only performed once, but is permanently installed.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Therefore, the query is continuously executed until it is explicitly uninstalled.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Since most DSMS are data-driven, a continuous query produces new results as long as new data arrive at the system.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] This basic concept is similar to complex event processing so that both technologies are partially coalescing.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] One important feature of a DSMS is the possibility to handle potentially infinite and rapidly changing data streams by offering flexible processing at the same time, although there are only limited resources such as main memory.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] The following table provides various principles of DSMS and compares them to traditional DBMS.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] One of the biggest challenges for a DSMS is to handle potentially infinite data streams using a fixed amount of memory and no random access to the data.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] There are different approaches to limit the amount of data in one pass, which can be divided into two classes.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] For the one hand, there are compression techniques that try to summarize the data and for the other hand there are window techniques that try to portion the data into (finite) parts.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] The idea behind compression techniques is to maintain only a synopsis of the data, but not all (raw) data points of the data stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] The algorithms range from selecting random data points called sampling to summarization using histograms, wavelets or sketching.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] One simple example of a compression is the continuous calculation of an average.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Instead of memorizing each data point, the synopsis only holds the sum and the number of items.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] The average can be calculated by dividing the sum by the number.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] However, it should be mentioned that synopses cannot reflect the data accurately.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Thus, a processing that is based on synopses may produce inaccurate results.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Instead of using synopses to compress the characteristics of the whole data streams, window techniques only look on a portion of the data.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] This approach is motivated by the idea that only the most recent data are relevant.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Therefore, a window continuously cuts out a part of the data stream, e.g. the last ten data stream elements, and only considers these elements during the processing.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] There are different kinds of such windows like sliding windows that are similar to FIFO lists or tumbling windows that cut out disjoint parts.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Furthermore, the windows can also be differentiated into element-based windows, e.g., to consider the last ten elements, or time-based windows, e.g., to consider the last ten seconds of data.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] There are also different approaches to implementing windows.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] There are, for example, approaches that use timestamps or time intervals for system-wide windows or buffer-based windows for each single processing step.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Sliding-window query processing is also suitable to being implemented in parallel processors by exploiting parallelism between different windows and/or within each window extent.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Since there are a lot of prototypes, there is no standardized architecture.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] However, most DSMS are based on the query processing in DBMS by using declarative languages to express queries, which are translated into a plan of operators.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] These plans can be optimized and executed.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] A query processing often consists of the following steps.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] The formulation of queries is mostly done using declarative languages like SQL in DBMS.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Since there are no standardized query languages to express continuous queries, there are a lot of languages and variations.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] However, most of them are based on SQL, such as the Continuous Query Language (CQL), StreamSQL and ESP.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] There are also graphical approaches where each processing step is a box and the processing flow is expressed by arrows between the boxes.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] The language strongly depends on the processing model.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] For example, if windows are used for the processing, the definition of a window has to be expressed.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] This stream continuously calculates the average value of "price" of the last 10 tuples, but only considers those tuples whose prices are greater than 100.0.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] In the next step, the declarative query is translated into a logical query plan.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] A query plan is a directed graph where the nodes are operators and the edges describe the processing flow.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Each operator in the query plan encapsulates the semantic of a specific operation, such as filtering or aggregation.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] In DSMSs that process relational data streams, the operators are equal or similar to the operators of the Relational algebra, so that there are operators for selection, projection, join, and set operations.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] This operator concept allows the very flexible and versatile processing of a DSMS.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] The logical query plan can be optimized, which strongly depends on the streaming model.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] The basic concepts for optimizing continuous queries are equal to those from database systems.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] If there are relational data streams and the logical query plan is based on relational operators from the Relational algebra, a query optimizer can use the algebraic equivalences to optimize the plan.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] These may be, for example, to push selection operators down to the sources, because they are not so computationally intensive like join operators.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Furthermore, there are also cost-based optimization techniques like in DBMS, where a query plan with the lowest costs is chosen from different equivalent query plans.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] One example is to choose the order of two successive join operators.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] In DBMS this decision is mostly done by certain statistics of the involved databases.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] But, since the data of a data streams is unknown in advance, there are no such statistics in a DSMS.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] However, it is possible to observe a data stream for a certain time to obtain some statistics.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Using these statistics, the query can also be optimized later.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] So, in contrast to a DBMS, some DSMS allows to optimize the query even during runtime.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Therefore, a DSMS needs some plan migration strategies to replace a running query plan with a new one.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Since a logical operator is only responsible for the semantics of an operation but does not consist of any algorithms, the logical query plan must be transformed into an executable counterpart.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] The distinction between a logical and a physical operator plan allows more than one implementation for the same logical operator.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] The join, for example, is logically the same, although it can be implemented by different algorithms like a Nested loop join or a Sort-merge join.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Notice, these algorithms also strongly depend on the used stream and processing model.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Finally, the query is available as a physical query plan.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Since the physical query plan consists of executable algorithms, it can be directly executed.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] For this, the physical query plan is installed into the system.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] The bottom of the graph (of the query plan) is connected to the incoming sources, which can be everything like connectors to sensors.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] The top of the graph is connected to the outgoing sinks, which may be for example a visualization.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Since most DSMSs are data-driven, a query is executed by pushing the incoming data elements from the source through the query plan to the sink.
[src:count-min-sketch/data-stream-management-system] Each time when a data element passes an operator, the operator performs its specific operation on the data element and forwards the result to all successive operators.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A **hash function** is any function that can be used to map data of arbitrary size to fixed-size values, though there are some hash functions that support variable-length output.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The values returned by a hash function are called *hash values*, *hash codes*, (*hash/message*) *digests*, or simply *hashes*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The values are usually used to index a fixed-size table called a *hash table*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Use of a hash function to index a hash table is called *hashing* or *scatter-storage addressing*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Hash functions and their associated hash tables are used in data storage and retrieval applications to access data in a small and nearly constant time per retrieval.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] They require an amount of storage space only fractionally greater than the total space required for the data or records themselves.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Hashing is a way to access data quickly and efficiently.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Unlike lists or trees, it provides near-constant access time.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] It also uses much less storage than trying to store all possible keys directly, especially when keys are large or variable in length.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Use of hash functions relies on statistical properties of key and function interaction: worst-case behavior is intolerably bad but rare, and average-case behavior can be nearly optimal (minimal collision).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Hash functions are related to (and often confused with) checksums, check digits, fingerprints, lossy compression, randomization functions, error-correcting codes, and ciphers.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Although the concepts overlap to some extent, each one has its own uses and requirements and is designed and optimized differently.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The hash function differs from these concepts mainly in terms of data integrity.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Hash tables may use non-cryptographic hash functions, while cryptographic hash functions are used in cybersecurity to secure sensitive data such as passwords.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In a hash table, a hash function takes a key as an input, which is associated with a datum or record and used to identify it to the data storage and retrieval application.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The keys may be fixed-length, like an integer, or variable-length, like a name.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In some cases, the key is the datum itself.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The output is a hash code used to index a hash table holding the data or records, or pointers to them.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A good hash function satisfies two basic properties: it should be very fast to compute, and it should minimize duplication of output values (collisions).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Hash functions rely on generating favorable probability distributions for their effectiveness, reducing access time to nearly constant.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] High table loading factors, pathological key sets, and poorly designed hash functions can result in access times approaching linear in the number of items in the table.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Hash functions can be designed to give the best worst-case performance, good performance under high table loading factors, and in special cases, perfect (collisionless) mapping of keys into hash codes.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Implementation is based on parity-preserving bit operations (XOR and ADD), multiply, or divide.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A necessary adjunct to the hash function is a collision-resolution method that employs an auxiliary data structure like linked lists, or systematic probing of the table to find an empty slot.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Hash functions are used in conjunction with hash tables to store and retrieve data items or data records.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The hash function translates the key associated with each datum or record into a hash code, which is used to index the hash table.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] When an item is to be added to the table, the hash code may index an empty slot (also called a bucket), in which case the item is added to the table there.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If the hash code indexes a full slot, then some kind of collision resolution is required: the new item may be omitted (not added to the table), or replace the old item, or be added to the table in some other location by a specified procedure.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] That procedure depends on the structure of the hash table.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In *chained hashing*, each slot is the head of a linked list or chain, and items that collide at the slot are added to the chain.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Chains may be kept in random order and searched linearly, or in serial order, or as a self-ordering list by frequency to speed up access.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In *open address hashing*, the table is probed starting from the occupied slot in a specified manner, usually by linear probing, quadratic probing, or double hashing until an open slot is located or the entire table is probed (overflow).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Searching for the item follows the same procedure until the item is located, an open slot is found, or the entire table has been searched (item not in table).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Hash functions are also used to build caches for large data sets stored in slow media.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A cache is generally simpler than a hashed search table, since any collision can be resolved by discarding or writing back the older of the two colliding items.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Hash functions are an essential ingredient of the Bloom filter, a space-efficient probabilistic data structure that is used to test whether an element is a member of a set.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A special case of hashing is known as geometric hashing or the *grid method*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In these applications, the set of all inputs is some sort of metric space, and the hashing function can be interpreted as a partition of that space into a grid of *cells*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The table is often an array with two or more indices (called a *grid file*, *grid index*, *bucket grid*, and similar names), and the hash function returns an index tuple.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Hash tables are also used to implement associative arrays and dynamic sets.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A good hash function should map the expected inputs as evenly as possible over its output range.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] That is, every hash value in the output range should be generated with roughly the same probability.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The reason for this requirement is that the cost of hashing-based methods goes up sharply as the number of *collisions* — pairs of inputs that are mapped to the same hash value — increases.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If some hash values are more likely to occur than others, then a larger fraction of the lookup operations will have to search through a larger set of colliding table entries.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This criterion only requires the value to be *uniformly distributed*, not *random* in any sense.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A good randomizing function is (barring computational efficiency concerns) generally a good choice as a hash function, but the converse need not be true.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Hash tables often contain only a small subset of the valid inputs.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] For instance, a club membership list may contain only a hundred or so member names, out of the very large set of all possible names.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In these cases, the uniformity criterion should hold for almost all typical subsets of entries that may be found in the table, not just for the global set of all possible entries.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In other words, if a typical set of *m* records is hashed to *n* table slots, then the probability of a bucket receiving many more than *m*/*n* records should be vanishingly small.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In particular, if *m* < *n*, then very few buckets should have more than one or two records.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A small number of collisions is virtually inevitable, even if *n* is much larger than *m*—see the birthday problem.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In special cases when the keys are known in advance and the key set is static, a hash function can be found that achieves absolute (or collisionless) uniformity.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Such a hash function is said to be *perfect*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] There is no algorithmic way of constructing such a function—searching for one is a factorial function of the number of keys to be mapped versus the number of table slots that they are mapped into.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] When testing a hash function, the uniformity of the distribution of hash values can be evaluated by the chi-squared test.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This test is a goodness-of-fit measure: it is the actual distribution of items in buckets versus the expected (or uniform) distribution of items.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] where n is the number of keys, m is the number of buckets, and *b**j* is the number of items in bucket j.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A ratio within one confidence interval (such as 0.95 to 1.05) is indicative that the hash function evaluated has an expected uniform distribution.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Hash functions can have some technical properties that make it more likely that they will have a uniform distribution when applied.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] One is the strict avalanche criterion: whenever a single input bit is complemented, each of the output bits changes with a 50% probability.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The reason for this property is that selected subsets of the keyspace may have low variability.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] For the output to be uniformly distributed, a low amount of variability, even one bit, should translate into a high amount of variability (i.e. distribution over the tablespace) in the output.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Each bit should change with a probability of 50% because, if some bits are reluctant to change, then the keys become clustered around those values.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If the bits want to change too readily, then the mapping is approaching a fixed XOR function of a single bit.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Standard tests for this property have been described in the literature.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The relevance of the criterion to a multiplicative hash function is assessed here.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In data storage and retrieval applications, the use of a hash function is a trade-off between search time and data storage space.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If search time were unbounded, then a very compact unordered linear list would be the best medium; if storage space were unbounded, then a randomly accessible structure indexable by the key-value would be very large and very sparse, but very fast.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A hash function takes a finite amount of time to map a potentially large keyspace to a feasible amount of storage space searchable in a bounded amount of time regardless of the number of keys.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In most applications, the hash function should be computable with minimum latency and secondarily in a minimum number of instructions.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Computational complexity varies with the number of instructions required and latency of individual instructions, with the simplest being the bitwise methods (folding), followed by the multiplicative methods, and the most complex (slowest) are the division-based methods.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Because collisions should be infrequent, and cause a marginal delay but are otherwise harmless, it is usually preferable to choose a faster hash function over one that needs more computation but saves a few collisions.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Division-based implementations can be of particular concern because a division requires multiple cycles on nearly all processor microarchitectures.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Division (modulo) by a constant can be inverted to become a multiplication by the word-size multiplicative-inverse of that constant.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This can be done by the programmer, or by the compiler.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Division can also be reduced directly into a series of shift-subtracts and shift-adds, though minimizing the number of such operations required is a daunting problem; the number of machine-language instructions resulting may be more than a dozen and swamp the pipeline.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If the microarchitecture has hardware multiply functional units, then the multiply-by-inverse is likely a better approach.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] We can allow the table size *n* to not be a power of 2 and still not have to perform any remainder or division operation, as these computations are sometimes costly.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] For example, let *n* be significantly less than 2*b*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Consider a pseudorandom number generator function *P*(key) that is uniform on the interval [0, 2*b* − 1].
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A hash function uniform on the interval [0, *n* − 1] is *n* *P*(key) / 2*b*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] We can replace the division by a (possibly faster) right bit shift: *n P*(key) >> *b*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If keys are being hashed repeatedly, and the hash function is costly, then computing time can be saved by precomputing the hash codes and storing them with the keys.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Matching hash codes almost certainly means that the keys are identical.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This technique is used for the transposition table in game-playing programs, which stores a 64-bit hashed representation of the board position.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A *universal hashing* scheme is a randomized algorithm that selects a hash function *h* among a family of such functions, in such a way that the probability of a collision of any two distinct keys is 1/*m*, where *m* is the number of distinct hash values desired—independently of the two keys.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Universal hashing ensures (in a probabilistic sense) that the hash function application will behave as well as if it were using a random function, for any distribution of the input data.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] It will, however, have more collisions than perfect hashing and may require more operations than a special-purpose hash function.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A hash function that allows only certain table sizes or strings only up to a certain length, or cannot accept a seed (i.e. allow double hashing) is less useful than one that does.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A hash function is applicable in a variety of situations.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A hash procedure must be deterministic—for a given input value, it must always generate the same hash value.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In other words, it must be a function of the data to be hashed, in the mathematical sense of the term.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This requirement excludes hash functions that depend on external variable parameters, such as pseudo-random number generators or the time of day.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] It also excludes functions that depend on the memory address of the object being hashed, because the address may change during execution (as may happen on systems that use certain methods of garbage collection), although sometimes rehashing of the item is possible.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The determinism is in the context of the reuse of the function.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] For example, Python adds the feature that hash functions make use of a randomized seed that is generated once when the Python process starts in addition to the input to be hashed.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The Python hash (SipHash) is still a valid hash function when used within a single run, but if the values are persisted (for example, written to disk), they can no longer be treated as valid hash values, since in the next run the random value might differ.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] It is often desirable that the output of a hash function have fixed size (but see below).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If, for example, the output is constrained to 32-bit integer values, then the hash values can be used to index into an array.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Such hashing is commonly used to accelerate data searches.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Producing fixed-length output from variable-length input can be accomplished by breaking the input data into chunks of specific size.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Hash functions used for data searches use some arithmetic expression that iteratively processes chunks of the input (such as the characters in a string) to produce the hash value.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In many applications, the range of hash values may be different for each run of the program or may change along the same run (for instance, when a hash table needs to be expanded).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In those situations, one needs a hash function which takes two parameters—the input data *z*, and the number *n* of allowed hash values.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A common solution is to compute a fixed hash function with a very large range (say, 0 to 232 − 1), divide the result by *n*, and use the division's remainder.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If *n* is itself a power of 2, this can be done by bit masking and bit shifting.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] When this approach is used, the hash function must be chosen so that the result has fairly uniform distribution between 0 and *n* − 1, for any value of *n* that may occur in the application.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Depending on the function, the remainder may be uniform only for certain values of *n*, e.g. odd or prime numbers.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] When the hash function is used to store values in a hash table that outlives the run of the program, and the hash table needs to be expanded or shrunk, the hash table is referred to as a dynamic hash table.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A hash function that will relocate the minimum number of records when the table is resized is desirable.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] What is needed is a hash function *H*(*z*,*n*) (where *z* is the key being hashed and *n* is the number of allowed hash values) such that *H*(*z*,*n* + 1) = *H*(*z*,*n*) with probability close to *n*/(*n* + 1).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Linear hashing and spiral hashing are examples of dynamic hash functions that execute in constant time but relax the property of uniformity to achieve the minimal movement property.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Extendible hashing uses a dynamic hash function that requires space proportional to *n* to compute the hash function, and it becomes a function of the previous keys that have been inserted.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Several algorithms that preserve the uniformity property but require time proportional to *n* to compute the value of *H*(*z*,*n*) have been invented.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A hash function with minimal movement is especially useful in distributed hash tables.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In some applications, the input data may contain features that are irrelevant for comparison purposes.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] For example, when looking up a personal name, it may be desirable to ignore the distinction between upper and lower case letters.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] For such data, one must use a hash function that is compatible with the data equivalence criterion being used: that is, any two inputs that are considered equivalent must yield the same hash value.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This can be accomplished by normalizing the input before hashing it, as by upper-casing all letters.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] There are several common algorithms for hashing integers.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The method giving the best distribution is data-dependent.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] One of the simplest and most common methods in practice is the modulo division method.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If the data to be hashed is small enough, then one can use the data itself (reinterpreted as an integer) as the hashed value.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The cost of computing this *identity* hash function is effectively zero.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This hash function is perfect, as it maps each input to a distinct hash value.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The meaning of "small enough" depends on the size of the type that is used as the hashed value.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] For example, in Java, the hash code is a 32-bit integer.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Thus the 32-bit integer `Integer` and 32-bit floating-point `Float` objects can simply use the value directly, whereas the 64-bit integer `Long` and 64-bit floating-point `Double` cannot.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Other types of data can also use this hashing scheme.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] For example, when mapping character strings between upper and lower case, one can use the binary encoding of each character, interpreted as an integer, to index a table that gives the alternative form of that character ("A" for "a", "8" for "8", etc.).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If each character is stored in 8 bits (as in extended ASCII or ISO Latin 1), the table has only 28 = 256 entries; in the case of Unicode characters, the table would have 17 × 216 = 1114112 entries.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The same technique can be used to map two-letter country codes like "us" or "za" to country names (262 = 676 table entries), 5-digit ZIP codes like 13083 to city names (100000 entries), etc.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Invalid data values (such as the country code "xx" or the ZIP code 00000) may be left undefined in the table or mapped to some appropriate "null" value.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If the keys are uniformly or sufficiently uniformly distributed over the key space, so that the key values are essentially random, then they may be considered to be already "hashed".
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In this case, any number of any bits in the key may be extracted and collated as an index into the hash table.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] For example, a simple hash function might mask off the m least significant bits and use the result as an index into a hash table of size 2*m*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A mid-squares hash code is produced by squaring the input and extracting an appropriate number of middle digits or bits.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] For example, if the input is 123456789 and the hash table size 10000, then squaring the key produces 15241578750190521, so the hash code is taken as the middle 4 digits of the 17-digit number (ignoring the high digit) 8750.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The mid-squares method produces a reasonable hash code if there is not a lot of leading or trailing zeros in the key.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This is a variant of multiplicative hashing, but not as good because an arbitrary key is not a good multiplier.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A standard technique is to use a modulo function on the key, by selecting a divisor M which is a prime number close to the table size, so *h*(*K*) ≡ *K* (mod *M*).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This gives a distribution from {0, *M* − 1}.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This gives good results over a large number of key sets.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A significant drawback of division hashing is that division requires multiple cycles on most modern architectures (including x86) and can be 10 times slower than multiplication.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A second drawback is that it will not break up clustered keys.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This technique works well in practice because many key sets are sufficiently random already, and the probability that a key set will be cyclical by a large prime number is small.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Algebraic coding is a variant of the division method of hashing which uses division by a polynomial modulo 2 instead of an integer to map n bits to m bits.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If *Z*(*x*) is constructed to have t or fewer non-zero coefficients, then keys which share fewer than t bits are guaranteed to not collide.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Z is a function of k, t, and n (the last of which is a divisor of 2*k* − 1) and is constructed from the finite field GF(2*k*).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Define $P(x)=\prod _{j\in S}(x-\alpha ^{j})$ where α ∈*n* GF(2*k*) and where the coefficients of *P*(*x*) are computed in this field.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Since α2*j* is a root of *P*(*x*) whenever α*j* is a root, it follows that the coefficients *pi* of *P*(*x*) satisfy *p*2 *i* = *p*i, so they are all 0 or 1.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If *R*(*x*) = *r**n*−1*x**n*−1 + ⋯ + *r*1*x* + *r*0 is any nonzero polynomial modulo 2 with at most t nonzero coefficients, then *R*(*x*) is not a multiple of *P*(*x*) modulo 2.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If follows that the corresponding hash function will map keys with fewer than t bits in common to unique indices.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The usual outcome is that either n will get large, or t will get large, or both, for the scheme to be computationally feasible.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Therefore, it is more suited to hardware or microcode implementation.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Unique permutation hashing has a guaranteed best worst-case insertion time.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Standard multiplicative hashing uses the formula *h**a*(*K*) = ⌊(*aK* mod *W*) / (*W*/*M*)⌋, which produces a hash value in {0, …, *M* − 1}.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The value a is an appropriately chosen value that should be relatively prime to W; it should be large, and its binary representation a random mix of 1s and 0s.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] An important practical special case occurs when *W* = 2*w* and *M* = 2*m* are powers of 2 and w is the machine word size.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] and for fixed m and w this translates into a single integer multiplication and right-shift, making it one of the fastest hash functions to compute.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Multiplicative hashing is susceptible to a "common mistake" that leads to poor diffusion—higher-value input bits do not affect lower-value output bits.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A transmutation on the input which shifts the span of retained top bits down and XORs or ADDs them to the key before the multiplication step corrects for this.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Fibonacci hashing is a form of multiplicative hashing in which the multiplier is 2*w* / ϕ, where w is the machine word length and ϕ (phi) is the golden ratio (approximately 1.618).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A property of this multiplier is that it uniformly distributes over the table space, blocks of consecutive keys with respect to any block of bits in the key.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Consecutive keys within the high bits or low bits of the key (or some other field) are relatively common.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The multiplier should be odd, so the least significant bit of the output is invertible modulo 2*w*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The last two values given above are rounded (up and down, respectively) by more than 1/2 of a least-significant bit to achieve this.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Zobrist hashing was originally introduced as a means of compactly representing chess positions in computer game-playing programs.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A unique random number was assigned to represent each type of piece (six each for black and white) on each space of the board.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Thus a table of 64×12 such numbers is initialized at the start of the program.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The random numbers could be any length, but 64 bits was natural due to the 64 squares on the board.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A position was transcribed by cycling through the pieces in a position, indexing the corresponding random numbers (vacant spaces were not included in the calculation) and XORing them together (the starting value could be 0 (the identity value for XOR) or a random seed).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The resulting value was reduced by modulo, folding, or some other operation to produce a hash table index.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The original Zobrist hash was stored in the table as the representation of the position.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Later, the method was extended to hashing integers by representing each byte in each of 4 possible positions in the word by a unique 32-bit random number.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Thus, a table of 28×4 random numbers is constructed.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A 32-bit hashed integer is transcribed by successively indexing the table with the value of each byte of the plain text integer and XORing the loaded values together (again, the starting value can be the identity value or a random seed).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The natural extension to 64-bit integers is by use of a table of 28×8 64-bit random numbers.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This kind of function has some nice theoretical properties, one of which is called *3-tuple independence*, meaning that every 3-tuple of keys is equally likely to be mapped to any 3-tuple of hash values.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A hash function can be designed to exploit existing entropy in the keys.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] If the keys have leading or trailing zeros, or particular fields that are unused, always zero or some other constant, or generally vary little, then masking out only the volatile bits and hashing on those will provide a better and possibly faster hash function.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Selected divisors or multipliers in the division and multiplicative schemes may make more uniform hash functions if the keys are cyclic or have other redundancies.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] When the data values are long (or variable-length) character strings—such as personal names, web page addresses, or mail messages—their distribution is usually very uneven, with complicated dependencies.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] For example, text in any natural language has highly non-uniform distributions of characters, and character pairs, characteristic of the language.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] For such data, it is prudent to use a hash function that depends on all characters of the string—and depends on each character in a different way.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Simplistic hash functions may add the first and last *n* characters of a string along with the length, or form a word-size hash from the middle 4 characters of a string.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This saves iterating over the (potentially long) string, but hash functions that do not hash on all characters of a string can readily become linear due to redundancies, clustering, or other pathologies in the key set.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Such strategies may be effective as a custom hash function if the structure of the keys is such that either the middle, ends, or other fields are zero or some other invariant constant that does not differentiate the keys; then the invariant parts of the keys can be ignored.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The paradigmatic example of folding by characters is to add up the integer values of all the characters in the string.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A better idea is to multiply the hash total by a constant, typically a sizable prime number, before adding in the next character, ignoring overflow.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Using exclusive-or instead of addition is also a plausible alternative.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The final operation would be a modulo, mask, or other function to reduce the word value to an index the size of the table.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The weakness of this procedure is that information may cluster in the upper or lower bits of the bytes; this clustering will remain in the hashed result and cause more collisions than a proper randomizing hash.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] ASCII byte codes, for example, have an upper bit of 0, and printable strings do not use the last byte code or most of the first 32 byte codes, so the information, which uses the remaining byte codes, is clustered in the remaining bits in an unobvious manner.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The classic approach, dubbed the PJW hash based on the work of Peter J.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Weinberger at Bell Labs in the 1970s, was originally designed for hashing identifiers into compiler symbol tables as given in the "Dragon Book".
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This hash function offsets the bytes 4 bits before adding them together.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] When the quantity wraps, the high 4 bits are shifted out and if non-zero, xored back into the low byte of the cumulative quantity.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The result is a word-size hash code to which a modulo or other reducing operation can be applied to produce the final hash index.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Today, especially with the advent of 64-bit word sizes, much more efficient variable-length string hashing by word chunks is available.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The final word, which may have unoccupied byte positions, is filled with zeros or a specified randomizing value before being folded into the hash.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The accumulated hash code is reduced by a final modulo or other operation to yield an index into the table.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Analogous to the way an ASCII or EBCDIC character string representing a decimal number is converted to a numeric quantity for computing, a variable-length string can be converted as *x**k*−1a*k*−1 + *x**k*−2a*k*−2 + ⋯ + *x*1*a* + *x*0.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This is simply a polynomial in a radix *a* > 1 that takes the components (*x*0,*x*1,...,*x**k*−1) as the characters of the input string of length *k*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] It can be used directly as the hash code, or a hash function applied to it to map the potentially large value to the hash table size.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The value of *a* is usually a prime number large enough to hold the number of different characters in the character set of potential keys.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Radix conversion hashing of strings minimizes the number of collisions.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Available data sizes may restrict the maximum length of string that can be hashed with this method.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] For example, a 128-bit word will hash only a 26-character alphabetic string (ignoring case) with a radix of 29; a printable ASCII string is limited to 9 characters using radix 97 and a 64-bit word.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] However, alphabetic keys are usually of modest length, because keys must be stored in the hash table.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Numeric character strings are usually not a problem; 64 bits can count up to 1019, or 19 decimal digits with radix 10.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] In some applications, such as substring search, one can compute a hash function *h* for every *k*-character substring of a given *n*-character string by advancing a window of width *k* characters along the string, where *k* is a fixed integer, and *n* > *k*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The straightforward solution, which is to extract such a substring at every character position in the text and compute *h* separately, requires a number of operations proportional to *k*·*n*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] However, with the proper choice of *h*, one can use the technique of rolling hash to compute all those hashes with an effort proportional to *mk* + *n* where *m* is the number of occurrences of the substring.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The hash function used for the algorithm is usually the Rabin fingerprint, designed to avoid collisions in 8-bit character strings, but other suitable hash functions are also used.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing, also known as similarity hashing, is a technique for detecting data that is similar, but not exactly the same, as other data.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hash functions, which are designed to have significantly different hashes for even minor differences.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing has been used to identify malware and has potential for other applications, like data loss prevention and detecting multiple versions of code.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Perceptual hashing is the use of a fingerprinting algorithm that produces a snippet, hash, or fingerprint of various forms of multimedia.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] A perceptual hash is a type of locality-sensitive hash, which is analogous if features of the multimedia are similar.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hashing, which relies on the avalanche effect of a small change in input value creating a drastic change in output value.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Perceptual hash functions are widely used in finding cases of online copyright infringement as well as in digital forensics because of the ability to have a correlation between hashes so similar data can be found (for instance with a differing watermark).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] Worst case results for a hash function can be assessed two ways: theoretical and practical.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The theoretical worst case is the probability that all keys map to a single slot.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The practical worst case is the expected longest probe sequence (hash function + collision resolution method).
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] This analysis considers uniform hashing, that is, any key will map to any particular slot with probability 1/*m*, a characteristic of universal hash functions.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] While Knuth worries about adversarial attack on real time systems, Gonnet has shown that the probability of such a case is "ridiculously small".
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] His representation was that the probability of *k* of *n* keys mapping to a single slot is α*k* / (*e*α *k*!), where *α* is the load factor, *n*/*m*.
[src:count-min-sketch/hash-function] The term *hash* offers a natural analogy with its non-technical meaning (to chop up or make a mess out of something), given how hash functions scramble their input data to derive their output.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] In the field of streaming algorithms, **Misra–Gries summaries** are used to solve the frequent elements problem in the data stream model.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] That is, given a long stream of input that can only be examined once (and in some arbitrary order), the Misra-Gries algorithm can be used to compute which (if any) value makes up a majority of the stream, or more generally, the set of items that constitute some fixed fraction of the stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] The term "summary" is due to Graham Cormode.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] The algorithm was presented by Misra and Gries alongside a different algorithm for finding frequent elements, the Misra–Gries heavy hitters algorithm.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] As for all algorithms in the data stream model, the input is a finite sequence of integers from a finite domain.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] The algorithm outputs an associative array which has values from the stream as keys, and estimates of their frequency as the corresponding values.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] It takes a parameter *k* which determines the size of the array, which impacts both the quality of the estimates and the amount of memory used.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] The Misra–Gries algorithm uses O(*k*(log(*m*)+log(*n*))) space, where *m* is the number of distinct values in the stream and *n* is the length of the stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] The factor *k* accounts for the number of entries that are kept in the associative array *A*.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] Each entry consists of a value *i* and an associated counter *c*.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] The counter *c* can, in principle, take any value in {0,...,*n*}, which requires ⌈log(*n*+1)⌉ bits to store.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] Assuming that the values *i* are integers in {0,...,*m*-1}, storing them requires ⌈log(*m*)⌉ bits.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] Every item which occurs more than *n*/*k* times is guaranteed to appear in the output array.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] Therefore, in a second pass over the data, the exact frequencies for the *k*−1 items can be computed to solve the frequent items problem, or in the case of *k*=2, the majority problem.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] With the same arguments as above, this second pass also takes O(*k*(log(*m*)+log(*n*))) space.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] Note that 4 is appearing 5 times in the data stream which is more than n/k=4 times and thus should appear as the output of the algorithm.
[src:count-min-sketch/misra-gries-summary] Since k=2 and |keys(A)|=k−1=1 the algorithm can only have one key with its corresponding value.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Suppose we see a sequence of items, one at a time.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] We want to keep 10 items in memory, and we want them to be selected at random from the sequence.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] If we know the total number of items n and can access the items arbitrarily, then the solution is easy: select 10 distinct indices i between 1 and n with equal probability, and keep the i-th elements.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] The problem is that we do not always know the exact n in advance.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] A simple and popular but slow algorithm, *Algorithm R*, was created by Jeffrey Vitter.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Initialize an array R indexed from 1 to k , containing the first k items of the input $x_{1},...,x_{k}$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] For each new input $x_{i}$ , generate a random number j uniformly in $\{1,...,i\}$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Return R after all inputs are processed.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm works by induction on $i\geq k$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] When $i=k$ , Algorithm R returns all inputs, thus providing the basis for a proof by mathematical induction.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Apply Algorithm R to the $(i+1)$ -th input.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Input $x_{i+1}$ is included with probability ${\frac {k}{i+1}}$ by definition of the algorithm.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] For any other input $x_{r}\in \{x_{1},...,x_{i}\}$ , by the induction hypothesis, the probability that it is included in the reservoir just before the $(i+1)$ -th input is processed is ${\frac {k}{i}}$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] The probability that it is still included in the reservoir after $x_{i+1}$ is processed (in other words, that $x_{r}$ is not replaced by $x_{i+1}$ ) is ${\frac {k}{i}}\times \left(1-{\frac {1}{i+1}}\right)={\frac {k}{i+1}}$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] The latter follows from the assumption that the integer j is generated uniformly at random; once it becomes clear that a replacement will in fact occur, the probability that $x_{r}$ in particular is replaced by $x_{i+1}$ is ${\frac {k}{i+1}}{\frac {1}{k}}={\frac {1}{i+1}}$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] We have shown that the probability that a new input enters the reservoir is equal to the probability that an existing input in the reservoir is retained.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Therefore, we conclude by the principle of mathematical induction that Algorithm R does indeed produce a uniform random sample of the inputs.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] While conceptually simple and easy to understand, this algorithm needs to generate a random number for each item of the input, including the items that are discarded.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] The algorithm's asymptotic running time is thus $O(n)$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Generating this amount of randomness and the linear run time causes the algorithm to be unnecessarily slow if the input population is large.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] If we generate n random numbers $u_{1},...,u_{n}\sim U[0,1]$ independently, then the indices of the smallest k of them is a uniform sample of the k -subsets of $\{1,...,n\}$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Now couple this with the stream of inputs $x_{1},...,x_{n}$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Every time some $u_{i}$ is accepted, store the corresponding $x_{i}$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Every time some $u_{i}$ is discarded, discard the corresponding $x_{i}$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm still needs $O(n)$ random numbers, thus taking $O(n)$ time.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Second simplification: it's unnecessary to remember the entire array of the smallest k of $u_{1},...,u_{i}$ that has been seen so far, but merely w , the largest among them.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm computes three random numbers for each item that becomes part of the reservoir, and does not spend any time on items that do not.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Its expected running time is thus $O(k(1+\log(n/k)))$ , which is optimal.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] At the same time, it is simple to implement efficiently and does not depend on random deviates from exotic or hard-to-compute distributions.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] If we associate with each item of the input a uniformly generated random number, the k items with the largest (or, equivalently, smallest) associated values form a simple random sample.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] A simple reservoir-sampling thus maintains the k items with the currently largest associated values in a priority queue.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] The expected running time of this algorithm is $O(n+k\log k\log(n/k))$ and it is relevant mainly because it can easily be extended to items with weights.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] The methods presented in the previous sections do not allow to obtain a priori fixed inclusion probabilities.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Some applications require items' sampling probabilities to be according to weights associated with each item.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] For example, it might be required to sample queries in a search engine with weight as number of times they were performed so that the sample can be analyzed for overall impact on user experience.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Let the weight of item i be $w_{i}$ , and the sum of all weights be W.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] The probability of each item to be included in the random sample is proportional to its relative weight, i.e., $w_{i}/W$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] It is not achievable when $k=n$ , since each item is then included with probability 1.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm is identical to the algorithm given in Reservoir Sampling with Random Sort except for the generation of the items' keys.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] The algorithm is equivalent to assigning each item a key $r^{1/w_{i}}$ where r is the random number and then selecting the k items with the largest keys.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Equivalently, a more numerically stable formulation of this algorithm computes the keys as $-\ln(r)/w_{i}$ and select the k items with the *smallest* keys.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] This algorithm follows the same mathematical properties that are used in A-Res, but instead of calculating the key for each item and checking whether that item should be inserted or not, it calculates an exponential jump to the next item which will be inserted.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] This avoids having to create random variates for each item, which may be expensive.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] The number of random variates required is reduced from $O(n)$ to $O(k\log(n/k))$ in expectation, where k is the reservoir size, and n is the number of items in the stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Warning: the following description is wrong, see Chao's original paper and the discussion here.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Chao uses interpretation 2: and Tillé (2006).
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] For each item, its relative weight is calculated and used to randomly decide if the item will be added into the reservoir.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] If the item is selected, then one of the existing items of the reservoir is uniformly selected and replaced with the new item.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] The trick here is that, if the probabilities of all items in the reservoir are already proportional to their weights, then by selecting uniformly which item to replace, the probabilities of all items remain proportional to their weight after the replacement.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Note that Chao doesn't specify how to sample the first *k* elements.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] He simple assumes we have some other way of picking them in proportion to their weight.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Chao: "Assume that we have a sampling plan of fixed size with respect to *S_k* at time *A*; such that its first-order inclusion probability of *X_t* is *π(k; i)*".
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Similar to the other algorithms, it is possible to compute a random weight `j` and subtract items' probability mass values, skipping them while `j > 0`, reducing the number of random numbers that have to be generated.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] In machine learning applications, fairness is a critical consideration, especially in scenarios where data streams exhibit class imbalance.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] To address this, Nikoloutsopoulos, Titsias, and Koutsopoulos proposed the Kullback-Leibler Reservoir Sampling (KLRS) algorithm as a solution to the challenges of Continual Learning, where models must learn incrementally from a continuous data stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] The KLRS algorithm was designed to create a flexible policy that matches class percentages in the buffer to a target distribution while employing Reservoir Sampling techniques.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] This is achieved by minimizing the Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence between the current buffer distribution and the desired target distribution.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] KLRS generalizes earlier methods like Reservoir Sampling and Class-Balancing Reservoir Sampling, as verified by experiments using confidence intervals, demonstrating its broader applicability and improved performance.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] The KLRS algorithm operates by maintaining a buffer of size and updating its contents as new data points arrive in a stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Suppose one wanted to draw k random cards from a deck of cards.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] A natural approach would be to shuffle the deck and then take the top k cards.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Note that although the rest of the cards are shuffled, only the first k are important in the present context.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Therefore, the array R need only track the cards in the first k positions while performing the shuffle, reducing the amount of memory needed.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Since the order of the first k cards is immaterial, the first loop can be removed and R can be initialized to be the first k items of the input.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Reservoir sampling makes the assumption that the desired sample fits into main memory, often implying that k is a constant independent of n.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] In applications where we would like to select a large subset of the input list (say a third, i.e. $k=n/3$ ), other methods need to be adopted.
[src:count-min-sketch/reservoir-sampling] Distributed implementations for this problem have been proposed.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] In computer science, **streaming algorithms** process input data streams as a sequence of items, typically making just one pass (or a few passes) through the data.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] These algorithms are designed to operate with limited memory, generally logarithmic in the size of the stream and/or in the maximum value in the stream, and may also have limited processing time per item.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] As a result of these constraints, streaming algorithms often produce approximate answers based on a summary or "sketch" of the data stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Though streaming algorithms had already been studied by Munro and Paterson as early as 1978, as well as Philippe Flajolet and G.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Nigel Martin in 1982/83, the field of streaming algorithms was first formalized and popularized in a 1996 paper by Noga Alon, Yossi Matias, and Mario Szegedy.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Semi-streaming algorithms were introduced in 2005 as a relaxation of streaming algorithms for graphs, in which the space allowed is linear in the number of vertices *n*, but only logarithmic in the number of edges *m*.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] This relaxation is still meaningful for dense graphs, and can solve interesting problems (such as connectivity) that are insoluble in $o(n)$ space.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] In the data stream model, some or all of the input is represented as a finite sequence of integers (from some finite domain) which is generally not available for random access, but instead arrives one at a time in a "stream".
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] If the stream has length *n* and the domain has size *m*, algorithms are generally constrained to use space that is logarithmic in *m* and *n*.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] They can generally make only some small constant number of passes over the stream, sometimes just one.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Much of the streaming literature is concerned with computing statistics on frequency distributions that are too large to be stored.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] For this class of problems, there is a vector $\mathbf {a} =(a_{1},\dots ,a_{n})$ (initialized to the zero vector $\mathbf {0}$ ) that has updates presented to it in a stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] The goal of these algorithms is to compute functions of $\mathbf {a}$ using considerably less space than it would take to represent $\mathbf {a}$ precisely.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] There are two common models for updating such streams, called the "cash register" and "turnstile" models.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] In the cash register model, each update is of the form $\langle i,c\rangle$ , so that $a_{i}$ is incremented by some positive integer c .
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] A notable special case is when $c=1$ (only unit insertions are permitted).
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] In the turnstile model, each update is of the form $\langle i,c\rangle$ , so that $a_{i}$ is incremented by some (possibly negative) integer c .
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] In the "strict turnstile" model, no $a_{i}$ at any time may be less than zero.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Several papers also consider the "sliding window" model.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] In this model, the function of interest is computing over a fixed-size window in the stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] As the stream progresses, items from the end of the window are removed from consideration while new items from the stream take their place.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Besides the above frequency-based problems, some other types of problems have also been studied.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Many graph problems are solved in the setting where the adjacency matrix or the adjacency list of the graph is streamed in some unknown order.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] There are also some problems that are very dependent on the order of the stream (i.e., asymmetric functions), such as counting the number of inversions in a stream and finding the longest increasing subsequence.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] These algorithms have many similarities with online algorithms since they both require decisions to be made before all data are available, but they are not identical.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Data stream algorithms only have limited memory available but they may be able to defer action until a group of points arrive, while online algorithms are required to take action as soon as each point arrives.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] If the algorithm is an approximation algorithm then the accuracy of the answer is another key factor.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] The accuracy is often stated as an $(\epsilon ,\delta )$ approximation meaning that the algorithm achieves an error of less than $\epsilon$ with probability $1-\delta$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Streaming algorithms have several applications in networking such as monitoring network links for elephant flows, counting the number of distinct flows, estimating the distribution of flow sizes, and so on.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] They also have applications in databases, such as estimating the size of a join .
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] The kth frequency moment of a set of frequencies $\mathbf {a}$ is defined as $F_{k}(\mathbf {a} )=\sum _{i=1}^{n}a_{i}^{k}$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] The first moment $F_{1}$ is simply the sum of the frequencies (i.e., the total count).
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] The second moment $F_{2}$ is useful for computing statistical properties of the data, such as the Gini coefficient of variation. $F_{\infty }$ is defined as the frequency of the most frequent items.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] The seminal paper of Alon, Matias, and Szegedy dealt with the problem of estimating the frequency moments.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] A direct approach to find the frequency moments requires to maintain a register mi for all distinct elements *a**i* ∈ (1,2,3,4,...,*N*) which requires at least memory of order $\Omega (N)$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] But we have space limitations and require an algorithm that computes in much lower memory.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] This can be achieved by using approximations instead of exact values.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] An algorithm that computes an (*ε,δ*)approximation of Fk, where F'k is the (*ε,δ*)- approximated value of Fk.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Where *ε* is the approximation parameter and *δ* is the confidence parameter.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Flajolet et al. in introduced a probabilistic method of counting which was inspired from a paper by Robert Morris.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Morris in his paper says that if the requirement of accuracy is dropped, a counter *n* can be replaced by a counter log *n* which can be stored in log log *n* bits.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Flajolet et al. in improved this method by using a hash function h which is assumed to uniformly distribute the element in the hash space (a binary string of length L).
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Let $\rho (y)$ represents the position of least significant 1-bit in the binary representation of yi with a suitable convention for $\rho (0)$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Let *A* be the sequence of data stream of length *M* whose cardinality need to be determined.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] hash space where the ρ(*hashedvalues*) are recorded.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] The below algorithm then determines approximate cardinality of *A*.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] If there are *N* distinct elements in a data stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] The previous algorithm describes the first attempt to approximate *F*0 in the data stream by Flajolet and Martin.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Their algorithm picks a random hash function which they assume to uniformly distribute the hash values in hash space.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Bar-Yossef et al. in introduced k-minimum value algorithm for determining number of distinct elements in data stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] They used a similar hash function *h* which can be normalized to [0,1] as $h:[m]\rightarrow [0,1]$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] But they fixed a limit *t* to number of values in hash space.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] The value of *t* is assumed of the order $O\left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon _{2}}}\right)$ (i.e. less approximation-value *ε* requires more *t*).
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] KMV algorithm keeps only *t*-smallest hash values in the hash space.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] After all the *m* values of stream have arrived, $\upsilon =\mathrm {Max} (h(a_{i}))$ is used to calculate $F'_{0}={\dfrac {t}{\upsilon }}$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] That is, in a close-to uniform hash space, they expect at-least *t* elements to be less than $O\left({\dfrac {t}{F_{0}}}\right)$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] KMV algorithm can be implemented in $O\left(\left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon _{2}}}\right)\cdot \log(m)\right)$ memory bits space.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Each hash value requires space of order $O(\log(m))$ memory bits.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] There are hash values of the order $O\left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon _{2}}}\right)$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] The access time can be reduced if we store the *t* hash values in a binary tree.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Thus the time complexity will be reduced to $O\left(\log \left({\dfrac {1}{\varepsilon }}\right)\cdot \log(m)\right)$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Alon et al. estimates Fk by defining random variables that can be computed within given space and time.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] The expected value of random variables gives the approximate value of Fk.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Assume length of sequence *m* is known in advance.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Algorithm takes *S*2 random variable $Y_{1},Y_{2},...,Y_{S2}$ and outputs the median Y .
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Where Yi is the average of Xij where 1 ≤ *j* ≤ *S*1.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Now calculate expectation of random variable *E*(*X*).
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] From the algorithm to calculate Fk discussed above, we can see that each random variable X stores value of ap and r.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] So, to compute X we need to maintain only log(*n*) bits for storing ap and log(*n*) bits for storing r.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Total number of random variable X will be the ⁠ $S_{1}*S_{2}$ ⁠.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] The previous algorithm calculates $F_{2}$ in order of $O({\sqrt {n}}(\log m+\log n))$ memory bits.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Alon et al. in simplified this algorithm using four-wise independent random variable with values mapped to $\{-1,1\}$ .
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] In the data stream model, the **frequent elements problem** is to output a set of elements that constitute more than some fixed fraction of the stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] A special case is the **majority problem**, which is to determine whether or not any value constitutes a majority of the stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] More formally, fix some positive constant *c* > 1, let the length of the stream be *m*, and let *f**i* denote the frequency of value *i* in the stream.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] The frequent elements problem is to output the set { *i* | *f**i* > m/c }.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Detecting events in data streams is often done using a heavy hitters algorithm as listed above: the most frequent items and their frequency are determined using one of these algorithms, then the largest increase over the previous time point is reported as trend.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] This approach can be refined by using exponentially weighted moving averages and variance for normalization.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Counting the number of distinct elements in a stream (sometimes called the *F*0 moment) is another problem that has been well studied.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] The first algorithm for it was proposed by Flajolet and Martin.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] In 2010, Daniel Kane, Jelani Nelson and David Woodruff found an asymptotically optimal algorithm for this problem.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] It uses *O*(*ε*2 + log *d*) space, with *O*(1) worst-case update and reporting times, as well as universal hash functions and a r-wise independent hash family where *r* = Ω(log(1/*ε*) / log log(1/*ε*)).
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Learn a model (e.g. a classifier) by a single pass over a training set.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] Lower bounds have been computed for many of the data streaming problems that have been studied.
[src:count-min-sketch/streaming-algorithm] By far, the most common technique for computing these lower bounds has been using communication complexity.
